dict.string: Aldwulf was a male dwarf bowyer residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Almar was a male dwarf working as a woodworker near Thorin's Halls, sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Alvari was a male dwarf working as a weaponsmith in Thorin's Halls, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]
Anar is a Dwarf character in the The Lord of the Rings: War in the North role-playing video game.
Ari Longarrow was a male dwarf bowyer residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Azaghâl was the King of the Broadbeam Dwarves, one of the seven Dwarf clans, and was lord of the kingdom of Belegost in the Blue Mountains during the First Age.

Balfor is a grey-bearded Dwarf from the Iron Hills. In TA 2941, he was captured by Goblins and forced to work in their mines in the Misty Mountains. Bilbo Baggins freed him from his cell by sneaking past the goblins guarding it and hitting the switch to open the cell, once free Balfor slew the guards and helped the young Hobbit how to escape.

Balin was a Dwarf leader, the son of Fundin, and elder brother of Dwalin. He was one of the twelve Dwarves who accompanied Thorin II Oakenshield on the quest to regain the lost kingdom of the Lonely Mountain.

Bávor was a male dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls, sometime before the War of the Ring. He sought to open the old vault beneath the mountain and eventually succeeded with the help of a Longbeard adventurer.[1]
Belg was a male dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Belgen was a male dwarf weaponsmith residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Bertel was a male dwarf working as a relic-master in Thorin's Halls, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]

Bifur was a Dwarf of the late-Third Age. He is best known for being a companion to Bilbo Baggins and Thorin Oakenshield on the quest to regain the Lonely Mountain, along with his cousins Bofur and Bombur.
Binír was a male dwarf working as a trader in Frerin's Court, sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Bjorni was a male Dourhand dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring. He was a tomb guard at the Berghold, where the tomb of Skorgrim lied.[1]

Bodruith was an Indrafang (Longbeard) Dwarf, of the kindred of the Nauglith. He was the Lord of Belegost. He was one of the wicked dwarves who appear in the The Book of Lost Tales. He was killed by Naugladur when starting a war between the two clans of Dwarves.

Bofur was a Dwarf of the late-Third Age. He is best known for being companions to Bilbo Baggins, Thorin Oakenshield and Gandalf on the quest to reclaim Lonely Mountain from the dragon Smaug, along with his brother Bombur and cousin Bifur.

Bogi, also known as Bogi Deepdelver, was a male Longbeard dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls. Sometime before the War of the Ring, he was one of the dwarves who participated in Dwalin's expedition to the Dourhands' lands, south of the city. He, along with some of his party fellows, fell ill to a strange disease but was healed afterwards, when a fellow Longbeard brought a cure. Some years after he served as a trader at Thorin's Halls' entrance.[1]

Bolli was a male Longbeard dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls. Sometime before the War of the Ring, he was one of the dwarves who participated in Dwalin's expedition to the Dourhands' lands, south of the city.[1]
Boltr was a male dwarf outfitter residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Bombur was a Dwarf who accompanies Thorin Oakenshield and Bilbo Baggins on their journey to the Lonely Mountain. His brother Bofur and cousin Bifur also were part of the company.
Bori was a dwarf from Lonely Mountain that met with Gimli and Gloin on the road to Mirkwood in TA 3017.
Borin was a Dwarf of Durin's Folk, the second son of King Náin II and brother of Dáin I.

Brúni Stonehelm was a male dwarf armoursmith residing in Thorin's Halls some time before the War of the Ring. He was brother to the guard Halli Shimmershield and at some point, he helped repair his brother's armor.[1]
Brymir Hammerhand was a male dwarf working as a weaponsmith in Thorin's Halls, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]
Dagg Dour-face was a male dwarf working as a weaponsmith in Thorin's Halls, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]
Dáin I was a Dwarf and a King of Durin's Folk during the Third Age. He was the son of Náin II and had a younger brother named Borin. He had three sons Thrór, Frór, and Grór.

Dáin II Ironfoot (or, King Dáin) was the son of Náin and the grandson of Grór, the youngest son of Dáin I of Durin's folk, and was lord of the Dwarves of the Iron Hills in Wilderland.[1] He was a Dwarven King of Durin's Folk, the fifth King under the Mountain, and the Lord of the Iron Hills during the War of the Ring in Middle-earth in the late Third Age.
Dannel was a male dwarf armor-smith residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]

Dori was a Dwarf of Durin's Folk, who along with his brothers Nori and Ori travelled with Bilbo Baggins as a member of Thorin and Company in The Quest of Erebor to reclaim the Lonely Mountain from the Dragon Smaug.

Dúri Bold-Hammer was a male Longbeard dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls. Sometime before the War of the Ring, he was one of the dwarves who participated in Dwalin's expedition to the Dourhands' lands, south of the city.[1]
Durin was the name of many Dwarves in the First, Second, and Third Ages, starting with Durin the Deathless, after whom the Line was named.
Durin VII was the descendant of Thorin III Stonehelm and possibly the last of the line of Durin's Folk.[1]
Durstan was a male dwarf armoursmith residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Dúsi was a male dwarf scholar residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]

Balin was a Dwarf leader, the son of Fundin, and elder brother of Dwalin. He was one of the twelve Dwarves who accompanied Thorin II Oakenshield on the quest to regain the lost kingdom of the Lonely Mountain.
Egil Oldbeard was a male dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Ekkill was a male dwarf residing in Noglond, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]
Fangluin Bluebeard was one of the wicked dwarves (Nauglath) of Nogrod told of in The Book of Lost Tales 2.
Farin was a Dwarf of the line of Durin's Folk.
Farmann was a male dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Fathi was a male dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Felek was a Dwarf Taskmaster from the Iron Hills.
Fengari Frostmere was a male dwarf residing in Noglond, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]
Flói was a Dwarf of unknown lineage.
Flosi was a male dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls, some time before the War of the Ring.
Frár is a dwarf of Durin's Folk that colonized in Moria during Third Age
Frerin was a Dwarf of Durin's Folk.
Frithbert was a male dwarf trader working in Frerin's Court, sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Frór (TA 2552 – TA 2589) was a dwarf of the Grey Mountains (Ered Mithrin) and was of the line of Durin.
Fundin was the son of Farin, the brother of Gróin, father of Balin and Dwalin, and uncle of Óin and Gloin, four of Thorin Oakenshield's companions on the Quest of Erebor.
Gagi Cloudbrow was a male dwarf residing in Thorin's Gate region, sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Galar was a Dwarf who lived in Nordinbad as a merchant, during the Third Age. He was the steward of Gorin.
Galti was a male dwarf working as an armoursmith in Thorin's Halls, some time before the War of the Ring. He was son to Geitir.[1]
Gamall was a male dwarf cook residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]

Gamil Zirak was a Dwarvish smith, who was the master of Telchar of Nogrod in the early First Age. Gamil was a great craftsman, whose work was found in the treasuries of Elu Thingol. He was commonly referred to as 'the old', Zirak the Old.
Geitir was a male dwarf residing in Noglond, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]
Gestur was a male dwarf working as a metalsmith in Frerin's Court, sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]

Gimli, son of Glóin, was a well-respected dwarf warrior in Middle-earth during the Great Years. He was a member of the Fellowship of the Ring, and was the only one of the dwarves to readily fight alongside elves in the war against Sauron at the end of the Third Age. After the defeat of Sauron, he was given lordship of the Glittering Caves at Helm's Deep.
Gísli was a male dwarf residing in Noglond, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]
Glasi Ironhand was a male dwarf working in Thorin's Halls, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]

Glóin son of Gróin was one of the dwarves of Thorin II Oakenshield's company who set out to reclaim the Lonely Mountain in The Hobbit, and was the father of Gimli, a member of the Fellowship of the Ring.

Gorin was the king of the dwarven delveng of Nordinbad (one of the locations in the video game The Lord of the Rings: War in the North, a mountain peak lying somewhere high in the wintry peaks of the Grey Mountains), during the War of the Ring. He is a character encountered in the video game, and is the father of Nordri.
Gormr Doursmith was a male Chief Dourhand dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the Quest of Erebor.
Gowan Smith-son was a male dwarf armoursmith residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Grimir was a non-canonical dwarf emissary who attended the Council of Elrond in TA 3018.
Grímkell Stonebearer was a male dwarf residing in Noglond, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]

Grithur was a male Longbeard dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls. Sometime before the War of the Ring, he was one of the dwarves who participated in Dwalin's expedition to the Dourhands' lands, south of the city.[1]
Gróin was the son of Farin, was a Dwarf of Durin's Folk.
Grór was the founder of the Dwarven realm in the Iron Hills and its first lord.
Gyllir was a male dwarf vault-keeper at Thorin's Halls, sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Hadhod was a Dwarf warrior, of the clan of Fundin.
Hagan Storm-sword was a male dwarf weaponsmith residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Hákan Ironhammer was a male dwarf armoursmith residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]

Halli Shimmershield was a male dwarf guard stationed in Frerin's Court, some time before the War of the Ring. He used a long axe as his weapon and was brother to the armoursmith Brúni Stonehelm, who at some point, repaired his armor at his request.[1]
Hannis was a male dwarf working as a weaponscrafter in Frerin's Court, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]
Hatt was a male dwarf trader residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Heikki Goldwatcher was a male dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]
Ibûn was a Petty-dwarf, was the son of Mîm and brother of Khîm.
Igul is a male dwarf Sergeant-at-arms stationed in Frerin's Court, some time before the War of the Ring, in the MMORPG The Lord of the Rings Online.[1]
Invar was a male dwarf armoursmith residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Ísleif was a male dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls some time before the War of the Ring.[1]
Islífur was a male dwarf working as a cook near Thorin's Halls, sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Ísrath was a male dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Ivor Yewbend was a male dwarf bowyer residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Jes was a male dwarf working as a tailor in the crafting hall of Frerin's Court, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]
Jímlí was a Dwarf blacksmith who would make Mithril items for his customers in the Third Age. His shop located at Bree.
Jolfur was a male dwarf hunter and hunting teacher residing in Thorin's Halls, sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Jórunn Firesong was a male dwarf working as an armoursmith in Thorin's Halls, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]
Kabbi was a male dwarf vault-keeper at Thorin's Halls, sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Kaupi was a male dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Ketill was a male dwarf residing in Noglond, some time before the War of the Ring, where he could be seen equiped with a mace.[1]
Kettil Hardhelm was a male dwarf residing in Noglond, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]
Khîm was a Petty-dwarf, was the son of Mîm and brother of Ibûn.
Kieri was a male dwarf armoursmith residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Kimbur Green-tree was a male dwarf armoursmith residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Kobbi was a dwarven combat trainer residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Kolfinn was a male dwarf residing in Frerin's Court, sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Kragg Stout-heart was a male dwarf weaponsmith residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Kyma Grey-bear was a male dwarf weaponsmith residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Kyn was a male dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Leiknir was a male dwarf residing in Noglond, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]
Litli was a male dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]
Loftur was a male dwarf residing near Frerin's Court, sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Lóni was a Dwarf of unknown lineage.
Lóthinn was a male dwarf healer residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Ludde Blackeagle was a male dwarf bowyer residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Makan was a male dwarf scholar in Frerin's Court, sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]

Mathi Stouthand was a male Longbeard dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls. Sometime before the War of the Ring, he was one of the dwarves who participated in Dwalin's expedition to the Dourhands' lands, south of the city. He, along with some of his party fellows, fell ill to a strange disease but was healed afterwards, when a fellow Longbeard brought a cure.
Mîm, or Mîm the Dwarf[1], was a Petty-dwarf of the First Age and possibly the last of the Petty-dwarves. He was mostly a part in the adventures of Turin Turambar.
Morór was a male dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Nagli is a male dwarf woodworker residing in Thorin's Halls some time before the War of the Ring, in the MMORPG The Lord of the Rings Online.[1]
Náin was a Dwarf of Durin's Folk.

When his father was slain by the Balrog, Náin I attempted to destroy it, but was himself killed the following year. The remainder of Durin's Folk fled Khazad-dûm, and renamed it Moria. He was succeeded on the throne of Durin's Folk by his son Thráin I who fled to the Grey Mountains and the Lonely Mountain.[1]
Náin II was a Dwarf of Durin's Folk and a King of Durin's Folk.
Nál Bellowsbreath was a male dwarf working as an armoursmith in Thorin's Halls, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]
Náli was a Dwarf of Durin's Folk.
Nár was a Dwarf of unknown background in the Third Age, a friend of King Thrór after the Dwarven Kingdom of the Lonely Mountain was taken by Smaug.
Nari was a Dwarven leader of the Iron Hills during the Third Age.
Narvi (fl. SA 750?)[1] (originally Ngarvi, Ñarvi) was a dwarf of Khazad-dûm (Moria) during the Second Age.
Naugladur was the Lord of Nogrod, the King of the Wicked dwarves of Nogrod in the earlier forms of the legendarium.
Naut was a male dwarf combat trainer residing in Thorin's Halls, sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Nisti was a male dwarf jeweller residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Nordi was a Dwarf first seen with his companion Bruni in Mount Gundabad fighting Orcs, Uruk-hai, and Trolls.
Nordri, in The Lord of the Rings: The War in the North, is the son of Gorin, lord of Nordinbad within the Grey Mountains (Ered Mithrin). He is voiced in the game by Nolan North.

Nori was a Dwarf of Durin's folk who lived in the northern Blue Mountains in Thorin's Halls and later the restored Lonely Mountain. He had two brothers named Dori and Ori, and was a remote kinsman of Thorin Oakenshield. His hood was purple, he played the flute, and he was very fond of regular and plentiful meals like his hobbit friend, Bilbo Baggins.

Nos Grimsong was a male Longbeard dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring. He was assigned by Dwalin to speak with the elvish party that had arrived in the settlement. He joined Dwalin's group to Skorgrim's tomb in order to stop Gormr Doursmith from resurrecting the ancient King.[1]
Óin was a Dwarf of Durin's Folk known for being a part of Thorin and Company during the Quest of Erebor.
Olin was a Dwarf of Durin's Folk residing in Thorin's Halls.
Ori was a member of Thorin's Company of Dwarves. He, alongside his brothers Dori and Nori, are remote kinsman of Thorin.
Ormr was a male dwarf residing in the region of Thorin's Gate, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]

Ovi Redforge was a male Longbeard dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls. Sometime before the War of the Ring, he was one of the dwarves who participated in Dwalin's expedition to the Dourhands' lands, south of the city.[1]
Ranald was a male dwarf armoursmith residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]

Refkell was a male dwarf fisherman residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring. He made one of his biggest catches in Ered Luin but the fish managed to escape his grasp. Afterwards, he asked a Longbeard to tell a friend of his, Nokki, of this feat.[1]
Reykur was a male dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring. He was a minstrel.[1]
Rhodri Blue-boots was a male dwarf weaponsmith residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Rúni was a male dwarf residing in the region of Thorin's Gate, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]
Rúnulf was a male dwarf and Inn keeper in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Rútur was a male dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Sandar was a male dwarf tailor residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]

Selur was a male Longbeard dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls. Sometime before the War of the Ring, he was one of the dwarves who participated in Dwalin's expedition to the Dourhands' lands, which were south of the city. He, along with some of his party fellows, fell ill to a strange disease but was healed afterwards, when a fellow Longbeard brought a cure.[1]
Sindri was a male dwarf weaponcrafter residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Skógi was a male dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring. He served as a guard at the city's entrance, using a spear as his weapon.[1]

Skorgrim was a male Dourhand dwarf King from ancient times. He led the Dourhands clan to attack the Refuge of Edhelion, an elvish settlement, seeking for the power of immortality within the relics the elves kept. He managed to destroy most of it but was stopped when an elf named Talagan brought the library's walls down upon them both, killing them and ending the conflict. Sometime before the War of the Ring he was revived by members of his clan and he started leading them once again.[1]
Smíthur was a male dwarf master craftsman residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Snár was a male dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Steinn Silvertongue was a male dwarf and the Bard of Thorin's Halls, sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Tandri Greyhammer was a male dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Telchar was a Dwarf of Nogrod in the Blue Mountains during the First Age.

Thalin is a Dwarf Hero created by Fantasy Flight games for the Lord of The Rings Card Game (based during the 60 years between when the Dwarves reclaim the Misty Mountain (Lonely Mountain?) and when Bilbo has to let go of the ring in Fellowship of the Ring). Thalin's name is similar to Balin and Dwalin from Thorin's Company, but they are not related in any way.
Thithrandi was a male dwarf weaponcrafter residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Thorin I was the son of Thráin I, and succeeded his father as King under the Mountain and King of Durin's Folk.

Thorin II, also called the Oakenshield, King under the Mountain or the Mountain King,[1] was the son of Thráin II, the older brother of Frerin and Dís, the grandson of King Thrór and the uncle of Fíli and Kíli. Thorin was best known for his deeds as leader of a company that infiltrated the lost Kingdom under the Mountain to take it back from Smaug and for leading an alliance of Men, Dwarves, and Elves in the Battle of the Five Armies.
Thorin III Stonehelm was a Dwarven Lord of the Iron Hills (presumably), King of Durin's Folk, and King under the Mountain.
Thorlák was a male dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Thráin I, also known as Thráin the Old, was the son of Náin I and King of Durin's Folk and the first King under the Mountain.

Thráin II was the father of Thorin Oakenshield, and the son of King Thrór. He became heir of the lost King under the Mountain and King of Durin's Folk as Thráin II when his father Thrór was murdered in Moria, and he was a direct descendant of Durin the Deathless.

Thrór was a King of Durin's Folk, the son of Dáin I, the grandson of Náin II, the father of Thráin II, the brother of Frór, and Grór, the grandfather of Thorin II Oakenshield, Frerin, and Dis, and the great-grandfather of Fíli and Kíli.
Thrymur was a male dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]

Tindr was a male dwarf residing in the region of Thorin's Gate, some time before the War of the Ring. He asked a fellow dwarf to help him repair the fissures in the walls surrounding Frerin's Court.[1]

Torri was a male Longbeard dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls. Sometime before the War of the Ring, he was one of the dwarves who participated in Dwalin's expedition to the Dourhands' lands, south of the city.[1]
Tórth was a male yellow-bearded dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Tryggwi was an old male Longbeard dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring. He usually carried a spear.[1]
Túki was a male dwarf vault-keeper at Thorin's Halls, sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Uffi was a male dwarf trader residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]

Unnarr was a male Longbeard dwarf residing in Thorin's Halls. Sometime before the War of the Ring, he was one of the dwarves who participated in Dwalin's expedition to the Dourhands' lands, south of the city. He was Captain of the Guard in the city. At some point he asked a fellow Longbeard dwarf to recover the weapons that had been stolen from the city's armory cave and soon discovered they had been stolen by the Dourhands.[1]

Varin is a Dwarf that appears in Sierra Entertainment's War of the Ring real-time strategy game, as one of the instructors sent by Gandalf in the free peoples tutorial (The other being the elf Belenthrod). He like most Dwarves likes battle, but does not like Elves. He considers himself an expert at gathering resources.
Vitharr was a male dwarf serving as a guard of Thorin's Halls' armory near Frerin's Court in the Thorin's Gate region, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]
Walgarth was a male dwarf barber residing in Thorin's Halls sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
Wárr Ink-Sleeve was a male dwarf notary residing in Thorin's Halls some time before the War of the Ring, in the MMORPG The Lord of the Rings Online.[1]
Wegeir was a male dwarf guard in Thorin's Halls, some time before the War of the Ring.[1]
Wíli was a male dwarf and stable-master in Frerin's Court, sometime before the War of the Ring.[1]
The Dourhands were an ancient clan of Dwarves that inhabited Eriador.
The Nauglath (or Nautar) are one of two Wicked dwarf clans appearing in The Book of Lost Tales. They were ruled by Naugladur of Nogrod. They are the kins of the Indrafangs (Longbeards).
The Stonefoots were one of Houses of the seven Fathers of the Dwarves that dwelt in the mountains of the East. They were originally paired with the Blacklocks.[1]
